A fascinating topic, whether to hit your kids... I believe it's an issue that is polarized to the point where &quot;discussion&quot; will not change either side's mind.  I know that my own opinion in this matter is firmly fixed.<br>
<br>
But this quote requires another look.<br>
<br>
If children respect their parents, they do not do so because they are afraid of getting hit.  If you respect another adult, it is not because you are afraid that if you don't, they'll pop you in the face.<br>
<br>
That is not &quot;respect&quot;.  That is &quot;fear&quot; or at the very best, &quot;caution&quot;.<br>
<br>
As is so often demonstrated in life, one person cannot demand or force the respect of another.  Rather, the person needing respect must make themselves strong and self-secure enough to where those around them acknowledge that inner strength.  <br>
<br>
That's quite a tall order, and I'm not sure where you go to &quot;learn how to be respectable.&quot;  From my limited experience in the world, it's clearly not something easily learned.<br>
<br>
With regard to children, of course they are CAPABLE at a young age of listening, understanding rules and recognizing limits.  I have one of my own, have coached little kid baseball teams, taught classes to kids, just hung around with them in general, and I have never yet met a single fully-developed child who was incapable of understanding about rules and how to follow them.<br>
<br>
I've also seen a lot of parents be incredibly ineffective with their kids, often those same kids I've had to coach and teach and hang around with.  Endless talking and negotiating, setting limits and then resetting them further out, yelling, hitting, the list goes on and on.<br>
<br>
They UNDERSTAND.  They may and often do choose not to care about following rules, but they understand them.  <br>
<br>
It is absolutely possible to impose rules and have them obey (with lapses on periodic occasions as they check to see if you're still paying attention)... but they will not do it if they do not respect the strenth within the person in charge.  None of us do as adults, and kids are no different this way.<br>
<br>
You can force a child to comply by inducing fear, if that is what you think is best for a child to learn.  But a child will not learn true respect because they see the belt in your hand.  True strength comes from within, not from a weapon.<br>
 <p>Khati Sha Rrraowl Ffffft<br>
